last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com: Because it's both banks you've probably got two clogged cats. The sporadicism is because if a cat is even 5% out of efficiency it will throw a code. Then when particulates clogging it burn off, it goes back. You can buy cataclean but I'd heavily recommend making your own. Ive looked at the MSDS and here's what I've come up with (I run an auto business and make my own for the same reason): 20% acetone, 15% isopropyl alcohol, 45% xylene. Make no more than 12 oz per 5 gallons. I say make your own because you need to run some through even AFTER the code turns off. There will still be obstruction in there and it's best not to do it half assed. Go to a quarter tank, pour it in, and then fill the tank between 5-10 gallons total. Run it through to near E then repeat two more times. Acetone for a gal is like $20, xylene is $26? for a gal, and you only need a large Walmart sized IPA bottle for the 3 mixes. You're welcome and God bless.

It's fine.

A fuse is just a piece of wire that's designed to burn through at a certain point so your main wiring/components don't burn through themselves. If nothing's wrong, they don't do anything.

A lower amperage fuse on a circuit that is designed for and pulls a higher amperage will just burn though the fuse in normal operation, but it doesn't hurt anything.
A higher rated fuse in a lower rated circuit isn't protecting it very well, but if everything is going right it doesn't do anything to the circuit.

The difference between 30A and 40A isn't much, anyway. The 40A circuit wouldn't have been pulling 30A in normal operation. burning though 30A fuses, and the 30A circuit wouldn't catch on fire at 40A.
So it's truly a nothingburger.
